'''St Mary's Church, Dodleston''' is in the village of [[Dodleston]], [[Cheshire]], England ({{gbmapping|SJ362610}}).  It is a Grade II [[listed building]].<ref name="images">{{citation |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?pid=1&id=55226 |title=Images of England: Church of St Mary, Dodleston |accessdate=5&nbsp;September 2007 |publisher=[[English Heritage]] }}</ref>  It is an active [[Anglican]] [[parish church]] in the [[diocese of Chester]], the archdeaconry of Chester and the deanery of Chester.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.chester.anglican.org/churches.asp| title = Churches in the Diocese| accessdate = 21&nbsp;June 2009| publisher = [[Diocese of Chester]]}}</ref>

==History==

A church has been on this site, adjacent to a former [[motte and bailey]] castle, since at least medieval times but only the base of its tower, which dates from the early 16th century, remains.  The remainder of the church was rebuilt in 1870 in [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|perpendicular]] style by [[John Douglas (architect)|John Douglas]].<ref name="images"/>  

==Architecture==
===Structure===

The church is built in red [[sandstone]] with grey slate roofs.   Its plan consists of a four-bay nave with a north aisle, a chancel with a north vestry, and a half-timbered gabled north porch. The two-stage tower has a short spire within its [[battlement|crenellated]] [[parapet]].<ref name="images"/>  It has diagonal [[buttress]]es and, on the west face, a four-light window.  On the south side of the tower is a small ringers' window and the belfry windows have two lights.<ref name="richards"/>  On the exterior north wall of the tower are pitted marks which are said to have been made by [[musket]]s fired during the [[English Civil War|Civil War]].<ref>{{citation | last =Morant | first =Roland W. | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Cheshire Churches |edition= | publisher =Countyvise | date =1989 | location =Birkenhead | pages =129&ndash;130 |  isbn =0 907768 18 0 }}</ref>

===Fittings and furniture===

Inside the church is a fragment of a medieval coffin, and a [[Royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom|royal coat of arms]] of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] dated 1660 on the west wall.  The tomb of [[Thomas Egerton, 1st Viscount Brackley]], who died in 1617, and his wife, Elizabeth, is beneath the tower.  The octagonal [[baptismal font|font]] probably dates from the 17th century. Late 19th century stained glass is in the east window.<ref name="images"/>  The communion plate includes a [[chalice (cup)|chalice]] dated 1732.<ref>{{citation  | last =Pevsner | first =Nikolaus | authorlink =Nikolaus Pevsner | coauthors =[[Edward Hubbard]] | title =The Buildings of England: Cheshire |edition= | publisher =[[Yale University Press]]| date =2003| origyear=1971| location =New Haven| page =200 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn =0 300 09588 0 }}</ref>  The [[ring of bells|ring]] is of six bells, the oldest of which date from about 1500, from 1618 and from 1681.  Two bells dated 1870 are by John Warner & Sons and the newest bell was cast by [[Gillett & Johnston]] in 1929.<ref>{{citation  |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=Dodleston&Submit=++Go++&DoveID=DODLESTON |title= Dodleston S Mary |accessdate=10&nbsp;August 2008|publisher= [[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]]}}</ref>  The [[parish register]]s begin in 1570 but are not complete.<ref name="richards">{{citation  | last =Richards | first =Raymond | title =Old Cheshire Churches | publisher =Batsford | date =1947 | location =London | pages =145&ndash;148}}</ref>

==External features==

The [[lych gate]] canopy and its wing walls are listed Grade II.  The lych gate has an oak frame on a sandstone plinth and a half-hipped roof of [[Westmorland]] slate with a red tile ridge.  The wing walls are of red sandstone.<ref>{{citation  |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?pid=1&id=55227 |title=Images of England: Lychgate canopy and wingwalls, St Mary's |accessdate=3&nbsp;November 2007 |publisher=[[English Heritage]] }}</ref>  In the churchyard is a [[sundial]] dated 1732.<ref name="richards"/>

